article.description:
Peja Stojakovic scored 26 points and hit a
3-pointer from the right wing with 1:39 to play to lift the Indiana
Pacers over the New Orleans Hornets 92-90 on Friday night.
article.headline: Stojakovic's 3-pointer lifts Pacers past Hornets
article.story:
OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Fortunately for Indiana, David West's buzzer-beater streak ended. Peja Stojakovic scored 26 points, including the go-ahead 3-pointer, and West missed a shot at his fourth game-winner of the season as the Pacers beat the New Orleans Hornets 92-90 on Friday night. "We dodged a hand grenade at the end of the game," Indiana coach Rick Carlisle said. "That was a great look and I know he's been making those shots all year long. We feel very fortunate." West, the only NBA player with three game-winning shots in the final 2 seconds of games this season, took an inbounds pass from Speedy Claxton with 3.1 seconds but came up short on a 3-pointer from the right wing. "That was a good look. I'm not going to get a better shot than that," West said. The Hornets had a final possession after Stojakovic missed a long 3-pointer with the shot clock dwindling and took the ball out of bounds with 6.1 seconds left after play was stopped because an orange toy ball was thrown onto the court. West took an inbounds pass and was forced to call timeout with 3.1 seconds left when he was swarmed by the Pacers' defense. Indiana's Anthony Johnson was called for a technical foul walking to the sidelines, but Chris Paul missed New Orleans' ensuing foul shot. That set up the final play. "We knew he was somehow going to touch it, whether or not he was going to hand it off to somebody else or take the shot," Carlisle said. "We had three straight timeouts to talk about it. We did a good job on the first two plays, and the third one they got us and got an open look. We're fortunate to be going back to the hotel with a win." After West had scored five straight points to put the Hornets ahead by one, Stojakovic connected from the right wing with 1:39 to play. It turned out to be the final basket of the game. Stojakovic scored 11 of Indiana's 17 fourth-quarter points. Johnson said he thought the Pacers sometimes boxed in the sharpshooter by running the pick-and-roll and counting on Stojakovic to pass too much. "We've got to do a better job of getting him on the move and coming off screens," Johnson said. "Tonight he showed us that he can get the job done coming off screens. So from now on, when the game's on the line those are the play calls that we're going to make and hopefully he can take us home." Stephen Jackson had 21 points on 9-for-24 shooting for Indiana. Johnson added 12 points and Jeff Foster had 12 rebounds as the Pacers avoided a third straight loss. West had 20 points, Desmond Mason and Kirk Snyder each scored 16 and Claxton added 11 for the Hornets, who lost their fifth straight game to match their longest losing streak of the season. The Hornets are 2-6 since winning five in a row heading into the All-Star break. "We've got to stay aggressive. Sooner or later, we're going to get one and put a run together," West said. "We've still got some time. I don't think it's time to panic or time to go away from what's been good to us, but we've got to get a win in the worst way." Two days after playing before a standing-room crowd in their return to New Orleans, the Hornets played before 18,506 fans at the Ford Center -- a larger crowd by 762 but not a sellout. They had little to cheer about early as the Hornets trailed most of the first half, mostly a result of 10 Indiana offensive rebounds that led to 14 points. Indiana extended its eight-point halftime lead to 60-50 on a tip-in by Scot Pollard. The Hornets then reeled off a 12-0 run that included consecutive dunks by P.J. Brown and Snyder that got the crowd involved. Back-to-back jumpers by West pushed New Orleans into the lead for the first time since early in the first quarter. Soon after, the game got heated when Mason and Jackson were each called for technical fouls for a confrontation after Johnson ran over Paul and was called for a personal foul with 5:12 left in the third quarter. Later in the third, Indiana rookie Danny Granger gestured toward the Hornets as he walked off the floor after being smacked in the face attempting to follow Jamaal Tinsley's miss. "It was an intense ballgame. When the game's on the line, you've got to make plays and things got a little physical out there," Johnson said.

Game notes
Indiana reserve guard Fred Jones will not need surgery on his injured left thumb. "It doesn't need surgery and there's a chance if it feels better and feels OK next week, he could play with a protective splint," Carlisle said. Jones, who hurt the thumb Tuesday against the Knicks, missed his second straight game with the injury. ... Indiana converted 10 offensive rebounds into 14 second-chance points in the first half. The Hornets had three offensive rebounds for zero points. ... Foster had eight rebounds in the first quarter, including six on the offensive glass.
